# Project: AI-Powered Fraud Intelligence Engine (Spring Boot + Spring AI)
# Role: Senior Java Backend Engineer / Architect

## General Constraints
- Write concise, production-grade Java 21 code.
- Omit boilerplate explanations; provide only implementation details and necessary context.
- Prioritize immutability: strictly use Java `record` for all DTOs and value objects.
- Favor constructor injection via Lombok's `@RequiredArgsConstructor`.
- Never use `System.out.println`. Always use SLF4J `@Slf4j`.

## Architectural Rules (Advisory Intelligence)
- The system is an Advisory Oracle, not a transactional authority.
- ALL LLM outputs must be constrained by the `FraudRiskLevel` Enum: LOW_RISK, HIGH_RISK, MANUAL_REVIEW.
- Prioritize the "Sad Path": missing data, low RAG similarity, or LLM timeouts must safely default to MANUAL_REVIEW.

## Observability & Fault Tolerance
- Every async boundary and controller entry point MUST include SLF4J MDC (Mapped Diagnostic Context) tracing with a `traceId`.
- Always clear the MDC context in a `finally` block to prevent thread-pool pollution.
- Any external call (LLM, Database) must be wrapped in Resilience4j `@CircuitBreaker` and `@Retry`.

## Spring AI Constraints (Anthropic Claude)
- Utilize `spring-ai-anthropic-spring-boot-starter`.
- Enforce strict structured outputs using Spring AI's `BeanOutputConverter`.
- When generating Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) queries, ensure pgvector cosine distance queries are explicitly bounded.